<paragraph blockId="21.[227,1437,994,1197]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Diagnosis based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Pike K. S. &amp; Graf G. &amp; Foottit R. G. &amp; Maw H. E. L. &amp; von Dohlen C. &amp; Harpel J. &amp; Pantoja A. &amp; Emmert S. &amp; Hagerty A. M." box="[461,667,994,1021]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="555 - 576" refId="ref11282" refString="Pike K. S., Graf G., Foottit R. G., Maw H. E. L., von Dohlen C., Harpel J., Pantoja A., Emmert S. &amp; Hagerty A. M. 2012. Eriosomatine aphids (Hemiptera, Aphididae, Eriosomatinae) associated with moss and roots of conifer and willow in forests of the Pacific Northwest of North America. Canadian Entomologist 144: 555 - 576. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / tce. 2012.49" type="journal article" year="2012">
Pike 
<emphasis box="[520,571,995,1021]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">et al</emphasis>
. (2012)
</bibRefCitation>
. Resembling 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Tullgren" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[824,1079,995,1021]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Pachypappella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lactea">
<emphasis box="[824,1079,995,1021]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Pachypappella lactea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but marginal wax gland plates on segments 
<quantity box="[377,450,1030,1056]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.89" metricValueMax="15.24" metricValueMin="2.54" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="in" value="3.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="1.0">1–6 in</quantity>
six longitudinal rows (in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Tullgren" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[745,844,1030,1056]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Pachypappella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lactea">
<emphasis box="[745,844,1030,1056]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">P. lactea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in four rows on segments 3–6). Legs, antennae and rostrum short and stout; tarsi 1-segmented, ant. normally 4-segmented. RIV+V without pale subapical zone. Dioecious, alternating between leaf galls on 
<taxonomicName box="[804,946,1100,1126]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Rhus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glabra">
<emphasis box="[804,946,1100,1126]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Rhus glabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[999,1087,1100,1126]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Rhus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hirta">
<emphasis box="[999,1087,1100,1126]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">R. hirta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(syn. 
<emphasis box="[1155,1243,1100,1126]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">typhina</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1254,1429,1100,1127]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Anacardiaceae</taxonomicName>
) and mosses (Bryophyta). In northern Europe anholocyclic on mosses. For detailed descriptions, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Pike K. S. &amp; Graf G. &amp; Foottit R. G. &amp; Maw H. E. L. &amp; von Dohlen C. &amp; Harpel J. &amp; Pantoja A. &amp; Emmert S. &amp; Hagerty A. M." pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="555 - 576" refId="ref11282" refString="Pike K. S., Graf G., Foottit R. G., Maw H. E. L., von Dohlen C., Harpel J., Pantoja A., Emmert S. &amp; Hagerty A. M. 2012. Eriosomatine aphids (Hemiptera, Aphididae, Eriosomatinae) associated with moss and roots of conifer and willow in forests of the Pacific Northwest of North America. Canadian Entomologist 144: 555 - 576. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / tce. 2012.49" type="journal article" year="2012">
Pike 
<emphasis box="[227,278,1171,1197]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">et al</emphasis>
. (2012)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
